WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Okay, let's go.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:16.000
Alright, today is Saturday, March 9, 2013.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:23.000
My name is Will Griffin and I am a research associate with the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, or History Program.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:42.000
I am with a videographer, John Bishop, and Albany Georgia on the campus of Albany State University to conduct an interview for the Civil Rights History Project, which is a joint undertaking of the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:49.000
We are here today with Miss Grace Miller who played a prominent role in the local Baker County Movement.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:56.000
Thank you so much for being here, Miss Miller, and agreeing to share your story with the Civil Rights History Project.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:03.000
So first, I would like to begin with you stating your full name, date, and place of birth.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:06.000
My name is Grace Hall Miller.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:12.000
My date of birth was due July the 21st, 1932.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:18.000
So could you talk a little bit about your upbringing, your parents, and...

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:21.000
Yes, my father was named Joe Nathan Hall.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:22.000
Okay.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:30.000
My mother was named Nanny Hall, and I was the sixth child, six of us, and I was the baby of the group.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:33.000
And we would be in the end of Baker County.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:37.000
My father was a farmer, and my mother was a housewife.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:46.000
I grew up with the school in Baker County, and church also, and I met my husband, he's the Baker County, too.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:56.000
His name was Jose Miller Sr., and we got married in 1946, then in 1946, in Baker County.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:00.000
And we got married secretly.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:06.000
And his oldest brother told the family he found out some way that we had got married,

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:09.000
because I had to go to school right on.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:12.000
And my parents were so upset because I was the baby.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:17.000
I didn't know how to cook, I didn't know how to wash, I didn't know how to do anything.

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:20.000
And he told my parents, they said, my baby don't...

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:21.000
She just can do it.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:23.000
And she said, you know what?

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:27.000
She said, whatever she does is fine with me.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:30.000
She said, you don't have to cook it, she don't have to go out to the house.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:33.000
I would do the cooking, my husband was a...

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:35.000
And I had his oldest in me.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:39.000
So we got married, and we had a beautiful married life.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:44.000
We had five girls and one boy.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:46.000
And he was a great father.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:50.000
Those girls, they took him from me.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:53.000
They were calling him, they had dad.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:57.000
And a lot of times I would be jealous because he would take them...

00:02:57.000 --> 00:02:59.000
He was just a good father.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:00.000
He could go on those kids.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:02.000
I wouldn't really jealous of the kids.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:05.000
But I wanted some of the attention that he gave them.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:08.000
And he would always tell me, say, you know you got my attention.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:09.000
Don't worry about it.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:11.000
You might be able to.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:14.000
And he found...

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:16.000
We had a farm.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:19.000
That was his occupation of farmer.

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:20.000
That was the house way.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:22.000
Taking care of the kids.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:24.000
And on March.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:28.000
Can we just back up a little bit before we move so fast?

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:31.000
I want to find a little bit more about your relationship with your parents.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:34.000
And the types of things that they instilled in you.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:35.000
You said you were the babies.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:38.000
So obviously there was a lot of attention built out to you.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:39.000
Oh, really?

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:41.000
So what do you remember about your parents the most?

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:44.000
Well, I was the baby of the family.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:47.000
And I was the teller to you.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:50.000
My oldest still will go.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:54.000
And my mama will say, take her with you if you want to go.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:56.000
And they will do things to them.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:58.000
Tell your mama and dad about it.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:03:59.000
I said no.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:02.000
That night when we getting the bed, I would tell them everything.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:05.000
So you're curious who you will aspire to.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:08.000
They knew I was the one to get the news.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:10.000
But I had a good mother.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:12.000
They were church workers.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:14.000
My father was deacon of the church.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:15.000
Okay.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:16.000
What church was this?

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:17.000
I was just talking about the church.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:18.000
I remember that church now.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:19.000
Okay.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:24.000
Do you remember some of the lessons there?

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:29.000
I mean, obviously religion and other things that they instilled in you.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:31.000
We had to go to Sunday school.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:33.000
We had to go to prayer meeting.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:37.000
We had to go to BTU at church.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:39.000
And they taught us value.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:42.000
My parents really taught me value.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:45.000
To treat others as I would have them treat me.

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:46.000
Right.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:49.000
And the main thing, my father taught.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:51.000
He didn't like for nobody to steal.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:55.000
And he taught us if you want something, you ask for one.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:58.000
And if you can't get it, then don't bother.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:04:59.000
Right.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:01.000
And it will stay in me until the day.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:02.000
Okay.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:04.000
That that don't have, I don't bother.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:05.000
Okay.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:07.000
And I taught my children the same thing.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:11.000
Be honest with whatever in their jobs, whatever they do, and to that.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:15.000
People that they deal with, be honest and treat them fair.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:16.000
Right.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:18.000
And that's the way I grew up.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:19.000
Okay.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:20.000
Loving everybody.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:26.000
I think if you go in my community, they'll tell you that I get along and I love everybody.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:27.000
Okay.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:31.000
And I grew up with that knowledge of treating people like you would have them treat you.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:32.000
Okay.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:35.000
So, let's talk about your early education.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:38.000
What were the schools like in Baker County that you attended?

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:41.000
My early education, we had a walk school.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:44.000
And it was about two miles from my home.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:45.000
Wow.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:46.000
And it would be cold.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:47.000
It would be real cold.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:53.000
And we would get the school and I would tell my dad, the teacher said, well, we need some wood.

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:58.000
And I'd tell my dad, when we get home, I said, dad, I said, my teacher, say, we need wood.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:01.000
I wouldn't sleep until he got that wood.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:03.000
He had to go get it.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:07.000
And stack it up and put it where I could see it to know that we'd have a fight at the

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:09.000
next day at school.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:14.000
And the kids had the bus to ride.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:20.000
They would pass through there with us, those spitballs after us and we would freeze them.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:21.000
They had a bus.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:23.000
But you know what, we kept going.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:32.000
That time, you didn't have any modest against them because we grew up thinking, you know, that's the way life was.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:35.000
And we were all back then.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:42.000
And from high school, I mean, from elementary, we had to go to Newton down to a city of Newton to the high school.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:43.000
Okay.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:45.000
What was the name of the high school?

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:49.000
Newton Baker County, color high school.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:51.000
They had Newton Colored High School.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:53.000
That's the name of it.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:58.000
But my husband's parents didn't let them go to school in Newton.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:00.000
He then drive to Camilla.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:03.000
All of his kids was educated in Mitchell County, Georgia.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:04.000
Mitchell County, Georgia?

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:08.000
Uh-huh, because he felt that I school just when I, you know, everybody at that time,

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:11.000
weren't able to take back his to out of the county.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:12.000
Right.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:17.000
But he was able to take his kids to Mitchell County, Georgia for an education.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:18.000
Okay.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:22.000
So, while you were in school, do any of your teachers stand out?

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:24.000
I mean, some of the...

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:25.000
Oh, yes.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:27.000
I was here for teachers.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:32.000
So, teachers that felt hard, you know, they were just dedicated teachers.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:34.000
Miss Granbare, one...

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:35.000
Granbare.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:36.000
She's from...

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:39.000
She's from Albany, Georgia.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:41.000
She taught down there in Baker County.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:48.000
We had Miss Smith from Albany, Georgia taught us.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:52.000
And we had a teacher, a principal name, is Bradley and the Erdo Metric Land.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:59.000
And we had to do what was right.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:04.000
We said, Bible verses every morning, we had to pledge allegiance to the flag.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:06.000
And we learned songs.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:07.000
And we learned poems.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:12.000
You know, and those poems and Bible verses is with me today.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:13.000
Okay.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:19.000
I think if you start off teaching a child at an early age about God and life and how to live,

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:22.000
you know, go along with them.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:25.000
But today's time, they can't teach that kind of thing.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:29.000
And I believe that's why we are having so much trouble in our school,

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:35.000
because they're not being taught the right, you know, about life skis.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:37.000
They're not being taught about it.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:39.000
Even now in our school, we don't have home making them own.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:40.000
Right.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:42.000
And see, those teachers back there taught home making.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:46.000
They taught you how to sew on buttons on your clothes.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:50.000
They taught you how to cook and how to save.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:53.000
See, now they don't teach those things.

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:55.000
And I cheer them, they're so wasteful.

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:58.000
And they don't know how to be upset, you know, how to save.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:02.000
And I think if we could go back to some of those old days,

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:06.000
our whole kind of world would be in a better shape.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:07.000
Okay.

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:08.000
Okay.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:11.000
So now what type of student were you in the high school?

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:12.000
I was good student.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:13.000
Good student.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:14.000
I was a little bit bitch.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:19.000
I would have one of those excellent, you know, A students all the way to the A and B.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:21.000
What you did, what you were supposed to do.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:23.000
So what year did you graduate?

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:25.000
It was in 50.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:26.000
50.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:27.000
Okay.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:32.000
And now let's move on to the time that your husband, as old folks say,

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:33.000
start courting you.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:35.000
When did you meet him?

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:38.000
And what do you recall about that first time you met him?

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:41.000
Oh, see, his parents are like, my, we had to go to church.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:46.000
And we used to go to B to you on the Sunday evening.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:48.000
B to you, what does that stand for?

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:53.000
That's for you, Bible, you've, Bible teaching you, you've planned.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:54.000
Okay, Bible teaching.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:58.000
And we thought he's talking, looking at me and talking,

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:05.000
and I was, Fred, I knew I was old enough to start dating, as they say.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:10.000
So he kept, was deaf, going to church, and he kept talking.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:14.000
And we secretly encoded because I wasn't really old enough.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:17.000
My parents didn't know I was dating.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:22.000
So after I got to high school, we stopped playing basketball.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:25.000
And I was living with my oldest sister.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:30.000
And that night, particularly night, he carried me home.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:33.000
And we started talking to each other.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:36.000
Let's go, Mary, you know, back then, those times you didn't have to have blood,

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:43.000
so we went to the probate in Gatmar, because how old were you?

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:44.000
14.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:45.000
14.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:50.000
But I was, he said, you could tell you going on school.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:51.000
We got married.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:53.000
My parents didn't know it.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:54.000
He would come back.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.000
So you were still living at home?

00:10:56.000 --> 00:11:01.000
Yeah, I was still at home, but I was living with my sister in high school,

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:05.000
because she lives in a little city where the high school was.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:07.000
We lived in country.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:13.000
But he would come to my sister's house, but he was afraid to go to my mom and dad to see her.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:19.000
So somebody, his brother found out, I guess he told his brother that we had got married.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:22.000
And his brother went down and talked to my mom and dad and told her,

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:25.000
so you know, people, you are married right here.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:28.000
And they said, yeah, I didn't know they were married.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:31.000
Marriage, how do you hear of anybody?

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:36.000
And they said, did you know your baby daughter had been there by baby brother?

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:38.000
And what did he say?

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:39.000
How did he know?

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:40.000
And dad is all dough.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:43.000
I know that's not true.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:45.000
But I guess they eventually got old.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:47.000
And they just crazed about him.

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:53.000
He was so nice to me, because just like I said, I didn't know how to end thing.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:56.000
Everything I did was by him with him.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:58.000
I cooked one day.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:01.000
And as I got older, I realized it was a mess.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:06.000
He said, I tell you what, let's not eat.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:08.000
We had rice and something else.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:10.000
He said, let's not eat it, because I had stirred it.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:12.000
I thought he was going to stir it.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:13.000
And he had got gum.

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:15.000
He said, I tell you what, let's not eat that today.

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:17.000
We go and get us something else.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:22.000
I said, okay, so we went and later on, he teased me about it.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:26.000
My sister came up there and they said, well,

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:29.000
you just said, I don't know how you making it.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:30.000
She kept cooking.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:31.000
He said, I don't care.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:32.000
It's good to me.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:35.000
Everything I cooked was good to him.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:41.000
He said, and my sister said, well, you see in there, because it's not good.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:45.000
And they kept that up, teased me all the time, but I couldn't.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:50.000
But I finally learned how to, because going to school and teach his home baking,

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:52.000
you know, and learning how to do a lot of things.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:54.000
And we got along really good.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:59.000
He never, he never got angry at me about anything.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:02.000
We just, we had all of the difference.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:06.000
But we always before we go to bed, we cleared up.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:09.000
I said, I'm going home.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:12.000
He said, if you go there, I'm going to.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:14.000
We lived together 18 years.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:17.000
And it was a beautiful 18 years.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:21.000
And as the kids grew, sure, it was my oldest daughter.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:28.000
And she was graduating at, and we were just looking forward to go, she wanted to go to Fort Valley.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:29.000
Before Fort Valley.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:37.000
And he taught, what he said, he said, when you look up, I'll be standing out there on that campus

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:40.000
and see what little boy you be walking around.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:42.000
And she believed in that too.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:46.000
I told him if he had lived, all of my daughters would be in old maids.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:50.000
Because he just didn't feel like they need to get married.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:53.000
Nobody was good enough for his daughter.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:56.000
I'm sure he would have changed it as they got older.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:00.000
But I teased him that son, if your dad had lived, you'd been old.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.000
They said, we know that.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
But he was a really good father.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:07.000
And I still miss my husband.

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:09.000
I've been 47 years.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:11.000
I never married anymore.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:15.000
And the memory of him still lingered with me.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:18.000
